s regulating social justice. Using a bottom-up approach through in-depth interviews with posted migrant workers and administrators involved in the posting process, Workers without Borders shows that strong labor-market regulation via independent collective bargaining institutions at the workplace level is crucial to effective labor rights in marginal workplaces. Wagner identifies structures of access and denial to labor rights for temporary intra-EU migrant workers and the problems contained within this system for the EU more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEmployee rightszEuropean Union countries. 0aEmployee rightszGermany. 0aForeign workerszEuropean Union countries. 0aForeign workerszGermany. 0aPrecarious employmentzEuropean Union countries. 0aPrecarious employmentzGermany. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aLabor History. 4aWest European History.  aPosted Work, intra-EU labour mobility, Germany, workplace study, European labor market.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501729171?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501729171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501729171/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles